title: Organize data
body:
- The format of `data(hgsc)` is now in sync with the functions of `diceR`, i.e. rows as samples and columns as features. This is done to make package data easily usable by functions of said package.
  - I understand the "norm for genomics data" as stated in #52 but someone using the functions would have to double check the input data format anyways, so no point providing package data that always requires trivial munging before using every time
- The original format of `hgsc` is now stored in `data-raw/` as `hgsc-raw.rda`
- The code used to transform `hgsc-raw.rda` to `hgsc.rda` is in `data-raw/hgsc.R`
  - Essentially the data frame is now fully numeric and transposed, moving gene names to column names, sample names to row names
- The example data objects used for debugging #96 are now stored in `R/sysdata.rda`. To load them into your global environment, run `load("R/sysdata.rda")`. This internal data object may be entirely removed in the future.
- Deprecated/temporary/intermediate objects `conClust_tcga.rda` and `E_imputed.rda` (previously in `data/`) have been removed from the package documentation/website
- Examples, unit tests, vignettes, README, website have all been updated with the new `hgsc` data format
  - Please take note
```r
data(hgsc)
dat <- hgsc[1:100, 1:50]  # do this now for subsetting
# dat <- t(hgsc[, -1])[1:100, 1:50]  # don't do this anymore
```

Once @AlineTalhouk and @billyhpchen have acknowledged this PR, I will merge this branch (or not, if we decide to modify/add/revert/etc.)

title: Additional methods of choosing k
body:
The changes in #98 have been implemented. Some code below shows the various scenarios:
```r
# Testing different scenarios for k.method, ref.cl, n

library(dplyr)
data(hgsc)
dat <- t(hgsc[, -1])[1:100, 1:50]
ref.cl <- data.frame(initCol = rownames(dat)) %>%
tidyr::separate(initCol,
                into = c("patientID", "Class"),
                sep = "_") %>%
  magrittr::use_series(Class) %>%
  factor() %>%
  as.integer()
data <- dat
nk <- 3:4
reps <- 5
progress <- FALSE
algorithms <- c("hc", "km", "diana")
cons.funs <- "kmodes"

# Scenario 1: ref.cl, choose best k/user-defined k/all k ------------------

scen.1a <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
                algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
                ref.cl = ref.cl, trim = TRUE, n = 2)
scen.1b <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
                algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
                ref.cl = ref.cl, trim = TRUE, n = 2, k.method = 3)
scen.1c <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
                algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
                ref.cl = ref.cl, trim = TRUE, n = 2, k.method = "all")
identical(scen.1a, scen.1b)
identical(scen.1a, scen.1c)
str(scen.1a, max.level = 2)
str(scen.1b, max.level = 2)
str(scen.1c, max.level = 2)


# Scenario 2: no ref.cl, choose best k ------------------------------------

scen.2 <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
               algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
               trim = TRUE, n = 2)
str(scen.2, max.level = 3)

# Scenario 3: no ref.cl, user-defined k -----------------------------------

scen.3 <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
               algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
               trim = TRUE, n = 2, k.method = 3)
str(scen.3, max.level = 3)

# Scenario 4: no ref.cl, all k --------------------------------------------

scen.4 <- dice(data = data, nk = nk, reps = reps, progress = progress,
               algorithms = algorithms, cons.funs = cons.funs,
               trim = TRUE, n = 2, k.method = "all")
str(scen.4, max.level = 3)
```

title: Feature prepare data
body:
Close #78 

Other bug fixes:
- majority voting consensus function is not guaranteed to output k classes because it depends on the mode across samples. In cases where `k_mj` < `k_ref`, we have to coerce the mj cluster assignment to a factor and make the levels equal to the reference cluster assignment. Then, when we do a cross tabulation there will be an empty row of zeros to make the confusion matrix a square matrix. Otherwise, the confusion matrix statistics cannot be computed and relabelling will not work.

title: Bugfix impute missing
body:
`impute_knn` is used before choosing `k` via `consensus_evaluate`. However, the `impute_missing` function is used afterward to fill in the remaining missing values in `E`. Please see the diffs for more details and let me know if you want something modified. 

We'll keep this PR opened and keep adding commits until satisfied, no merging till finished.

title: Feature prepare data
body:
User can now specify different options for preparing data:
- "full" prepares the data at the beginning 
- "sampled" prepares the sampled data at every iteration of resampling
- "none" does not prepare the data

title: Feature/custom algs
body:
User can now

- input custom clustering algorithm
- input custom distance function
- specify NMF-based methods

title: Feature/dice usage
body:
Changes:
- removed `consensus_confmat()`: unnecessary helper function; can generate manually if needed
- easier to navigate the different consensus functions by putting them all in `consensus_funs.R`.
- the family tag "consensus functions" now refer CSPA, LCE, kmodes, and majority voting to each other
- synchronize parameter names between `ConClust()` and `dice()`.
- implement CSPA, use average linkage (not changeable as of now)
- remove extraneous data input from `LCE()`.
- update `dice()` after `CSPA()` works
- **`ConClust()` is now called `consensus_cluster()`. We are standardizing function names to use underscores and move away from snake case.**
